TWO students at the University of Strathclyde have been diagnosed with meningitis, the university has said Strathclyde Uni students diagnosed with meningitis TWO students at the University of Strathclyde have been diagnosed with meningitis, the university has said.

The two cases are not thought to be connected.
Staff at the institution are working closely with health officials to make all students and members of staff aware of the signs and symptoms of the disease.
An email was sent to all staff and students this morning. 
The university, which was founded 218 years ago as the Andersonian Institute currently has around 19,750 students and was awarded the University of the Year prize in 2012.
Notable alumni include the explorer David Livingstone; John Logie Baird, inventor of the television and Clyde Blowers boss Jim McColl. 
 